House Sales in King County - Ceteris Paribus explanations¶

Author: Piotr Grabysz¶

Date: 2021-04-16¶

The goal of this notebook is to learn Ceteris Paribus (Latin phrase meaning "other things equal") techniques.

I use House Sales in King County dateset and try to predict house's price based upon following features

  • bedrooms - Number of bedrooms
  • bathrooms - Number of bathrooms, where .5 accounts for a room with a toilet but no shower
  • sqft_living - Square footage of the apartments interior living space
  • sqft_lot - Square footage of the land space
  • floors - Number of floors
  • waterfront - A dummy variable for whether the apartment was overlooking the waterfront or not
  • view - An index from 0 to 4 of how good the view of the property was
  • condition - An index from 1 to 5 on the condition of the apartment,
  • grade - An index from 1 to 13, where 1-3 falls short of building construction and design, 7 has an average level of construction and design, and 11-13 have a high quality level of construction and design.
  • sqft_above - The square footage of the interior housing space that is above ground level
  • sqft_basement - The square footage of the interior housing space that is below ground level
  • yr_built - The year the house was initially built
  • yr_renovated - The year of the houses last renovation
  • zipcode - What zipcode area the house is in
  • lat - Lattitude
  • long - Longitude
  • sqft_living15 - The square footage of interior housing living space for the nearest 15 neighbors
  • sqft_lot15 - The square footage of the land lots of the nearest 15 neighbors

The analysis¶

I choose three houses to perform the analysis on them (the same as in the previous notebooks):

price bedrooms bathrooms sqft_living sqft_lot floors waterfront view condition grade sqft_above sqft_basement yr_built yr_renovated lat long sqft_living15 sqft_lot15
low price 80,000$ 1 0.75 430 5050 1.0 0 0 2 4 430 0 1912 0 47.6499 -121.909 1200 7500
average price 540,000$ 3 2.50 2400 5817 2.0 0 0 3 8 2400 0 1998 0 47.5371 -121.870 2420 5817
high price 6,885,000$ 6 7.75 9890 31374 2.0 0 4 3 13 8860 1030 2001 0 47.6305 -122.240 4540 42730

Models' predictions for this three samples:

The real price XGBoost prediction Neural network prediction
465 80,000$ 150,118$ 197,709$
18838 540,000$ 539,440$ 498,552$
9254 6,885,000$ 6,908,374$ 5,985,286$

I decide to plot simultaneously CP profiles for my both models - XGBoost and neural network.

The first plot shows CP profiles for variables containing 'sqft' in their name.

Values at the X axis range from minimum to maximum of the adequate variable.

One can see here, that profiles made by the neural network are much smoother, as would be expected. The predicted price values are different, but quite often the trend is more or less the same. This goes hand in hand with the fact, that LIME decomposition (previous notebook) was very similar for both models.

We can see that sqft_living and sqft_above increases the price every time. The role of the other variables is more vague.

The most surprising variable to me is sqft_lot15 (the square footage of the land lots of the nearest 15 neighbors). Firstly, it is an example of the feature whose role differs for both models. In the case of XGBoost, changing sqft_lot15 has little or no impact on the price. But in the case of neural network, the predictions drop significantly while increasing the sqft_lot. It is totally counter-intuitive to me. What is worse, similar behavior is observed for sqft_lot for the expensive example.

Categorical variables¶

Grade was one on the most important variables for both models for LIME decomposition. But while generally increasing grade increases the price (very intuitively), I am surprised to see that for the low price example the impact of grade is almost no visible for the neural network predictions. And it is the very opposite for XGBoost.

Mentioning LIME reminds me that my LIME decomposition of these two models showed waterfront as the very important variable. I would like to see if its impact on the price is so visible yet again:

Yes, adding waterfront view doubles the price for in the case of both models for the low price and average price example. But for the high price example it lowers the price and I can't see the reason why.

Let's take a look at the remaining categorical features:

condition can boost the price, especially for the cheaper houses. view has almost no influence on the price.

I remember from my SHAP and LIME analysis, that the role of number of bedrooms, bathrooms and floors was almost no visible. Let's see if this happen for CP profiles:

The most visible feature of these plot for me is the fact that the profiles of neural network are much more variable, while the profiles of XGBoost are more constant.

X = house_data.drop(["id", "price", "date", "zipcode"], axis = 1)
cols_idx = {}
for col in X.columns:
    cols_idx[col] = X.columns.get_loc(col)
    
X = X.to_numpy()
y = house_data["price"]

I make train test split. Becuase the range of prices is very big I do stratified split to ensure that in both datasets the ratio of cheap and expensive samples is similar.

In [66]:
y_binned = y.apply(lambda x: round(x/1e+5) if x<2e+6 else 21)
bins = y_binned.unique().tolist()
bins.sort()

# now y_train is splitted y_binned. I want y, but with indexes from splitted y_binned

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from keras.models import load_model

batchsize = 500
dropout_rate = 0.2
neural_net_model = Sequential([
    Dense(256, activation="relu"),
    Dropout(dropout_rate),
    Dense(256, activation="relu"),
    Dropout(dropout_rate),
    Dense(256, activation="relu"),
    Dropout(dropout_rate),
    Dense(1, activation=None),
])

neural_net_model.compile(
    loss="mean_squared_error",
    optimizer="adam"
)

neural_net_model.build(input_shape=(batchsize, X_train_scaled.shape[1]))
neural_net_model.summary()

In [47]:
def cp_values_num(pred_fun, X, col_idx, sample_idx, n_partitions=100):
    var_min = X[:, col_idx].min()
    var_max = X[:, col_idx].max()
    grid = np.linspace(start=var_min, stop=var_max, num=n_partitions)
    new_X = []
    for g in grid:
        new_sample = X[sample_idx,:].copy()
        new_sample[col_idx] = g
        new_X.append(new_sample)
        
    new_X =np.array(new_X)
    y = pred_fun(new_X)
    return y, grid
In [71]:
def nn_predict(X):
    y_hat = neural_net_model.predict(scaler.transform(X))
    y_hat = scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_hat)
    return y_hat

sqft_var_names = ['sqft_living', 'sqft_lot', 'sqft_above', 'sqft_basement', 'sqft_living15', 'sqft_lot15']
sample_idx = cheap_house_idx

fig_sqft_cheap, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(30, 15))
axes = axes.flatten()
for i, var_name in enumerate(sqft_var_names):
    y_xgb, grid = cp_values_num(xgb_model.predict, X, cols_idx[var_name], sample_idx)
    actual_value = X[sample_idx, cols_idx[var_name]]
    actual_value_idx = np.argmin(np.abs(grid - actual_value))
    axes[i].plot(grid, y_xgb, label="XGBoost")
    axes[i].plot(grid[actual_value_idx], y_xgb[actual_value_idx], marker="o") 
    
    y_nn, grid = cp_values_num(nn_predict, X, cols_idx[var_name], sample_idx)
    actual_value = X[sample_idx, cols_idx[var_name]]
    actual_value_idx = np.argmin(np.abs(grid - actual_value))
    axes[i].plot(grid, y_nn, label="Neural net")
    axes[i].plot(grid[actual_value_idx], y_nn[actual_value_idx], marker="o") 
    
    axes[i].set_title(f"{var_name}", fontsize = 20)
    axes[i].set_ylabel(f"Price")
    axes[i].legend()
    
fig_sqft_cheap.suptitle("Low price example - sqft CP profiles analysis", fontsize = 20)
plt.show()

In [97]:
def cp_values_cat(pred_fun, X, col_idx, sample_idx):
    
    values = np.unique(X[:, col_idx])
    
    new_X = []
    for v in values:
        new_sample = X[sample_idx,:].copy()
        new_sample[col_idx] = v
        new_X.append(new_sample)
        
    new_X =np.array(new_X)
    y = pred_fun(new_X)
    return y, values

fig_floors, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(30, 10))
axes = axes.flatten()
var_name = "floors"
for i, sample_idx in enumerate(samples):
    width = 0.1
    y_xgb, grid = cp_values_cat(xgb_model.predict, X, cols_idx[var_name], sample_idx)
    axes[i].bar(grid, y_xgb, width, label="XGBoost")
    
    y_nn, grid = cp_values_cat(nn_predict, X, cols_idx[var_name], sample_idx)
    axes[i].bar(grid+width, y_nn.flatten(), width, label="Neural net")
    
    axes[i].set_title(f"{samples_names[i]} example: {var_name}={X[sample_idx, cols_idx[var_name]]}", fontsize = 20)
    axes[i].set_xlabel(f"{var_name}")
    axes[i].set_ylabel(f"Price")
    axes[i].legend()
    
fig_floors.suptitle(f"{var_name} CP profiles", fontsize = 20)
